2. Recap ‚Äì What We Learned Earlier
------------------------------------------------------------

Previous lecture me students ne seekha:

‚Ä¢ Flowcharts  
‚Ä¢ Pseudocode  
‚Ä¢ Problem ko steps me todna  
‚Ä¢ Computer ko instruction kaise deni hoti hai  

Real-life analogy:
Chai ya coffee banani ho toh pehle steps sochte ho,
phir unko follow karte ho.

Conclusion:
‚ùå Direct code likhna galat hai  
‚úÖ Pehle logic ‚Üí phir code  


------------------------------------------------------------
3. Why Coding Is Needed After Logic
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher puchta hai:

‚ÄúLogic bana liya, flowchart bana liya‚Ä¶
ab computer ko kaise samjhaoge?‚Äù

Answer:
Logic ko **CODE** me convert karna padega.

Flow:
Logic ‚Üí Code ‚Üí Compiler ‚Üí Machine Execution


------------------------------------------------------------
4. Compiler ‚Äì What It REALLY Does
------------------------------------------------------------

Important clarification:

Compiler sirf code convert nahi karta.

Compiler ke 3 kaam:

1Ô∏è‚É£ High-level code ‚Üí machine language  
2Ô∏è‚É£ Syntax + logical error checking  
3Ô∏è‚É£ Error ho toh execution rok deta hai  

Analogy:
Hindi ‚Üí English ‚Üí Computer language

Teacher bolta hai:
‚ÄúAgar error hai toh compiler bolega:
‚ÄòPehle theek karo, phir run karunga.‚Äô‚Äù


------------------------------------------------------------
5. Hardware Reminder ‚Äì Transistor
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher hardware ki baat karta hai:

‚ÄúTransistor sabko pata hai na?‚Äù

Transistor ke sirf 2 states hote hain:
‚Ä¢ ON  ‚Üí 1  
‚Ä¢ OFF ‚Üí 0  

Isiliye computer sirf **binary** samajhta hai.


------------------------------------------------------------
6. How Numbers Are Stored (Example: 5)
------------------------------------------------------------

Number **5** ko store karna hai.

Step 1: Binary conversion  
5 ‚Üí 101  

Step 2: Transistor state:

1 ‚Üí ON  
0 ‚Üí OFF  
1 ‚Üí ON  

Baaki bits ‚Üí OFF

Conclusion:
Computer har cheez ko ON/OFF ke form me store karta hai.


------------------------------------------------------------
7. Bits, Bytes & Memory Units
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher puchta hai:

‚Äú8 bits ek saath ho jaayein toh kya bolte hain?‚Äù

Answer:
‚Ä¢ 8 bits = 1 byte  

Memory growth:
Bit ‚Üí Byte ‚Üí KB ‚Üí MB ‚Üí GB


------------------------------------------------------------
8. Characters Are NOT Stored as Characters
------------------------------------------------------------

Important realization:

Computer characters directly store nahi karta.

Example:
'A' store nahi hota  
'A' ka **ASCII number (65)** store hota hai.


------------------------------------------------------------
9. Why ASCII Exists (Global Communication)
------------------------------------------------------------

Agar har country ka encoding alag hota:

‚Ä¢ Ek system bole 65 = 'A'  
‚Ä¢ Dusra bole 65 = '*'  

Communication fail ‚ùå

Solution:
‚û°Ô∏è ASCII table  
‚û°Ô∏è Fixed numeric mapping  
‚û°Ô∏è Worldwide accepted üåç


------------------------------------------------------------
10. ASCII Patterns (Completed Explanation)
------------------------------------------------------------

‚Ä¢ 'A' = 65  
‚Ä¢ 'B' = 66  
‚Ä¢ 'Z' = 90  

‚Ä¢ 'a' = 97  
‚Ä¢ 'b' = 98  

‚Ä¢ Numbers aur symbols ke bhi codes hote hain

Keyboard ka har key = ek NUMBER.


------------------------------------------------------------
11. How Characters Are Stored in Memory
------------------------------------------------------------

Flow:

Character  
‚Üí ASCII decimal  
‚Üí Binary  
‚Üí Memory bits  

Example:
'A' ‚Üí 65 ‚Üí 01000001 ‚Üí 8 bits me store


------------------------------------------------------------
12. RAM, Bits & Why This Topic Exists
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher puchta hai:
‚ÄúRAM kyun padhna hai?‚Äù

Answer:
‚Ä¢ Variables memory me rehte hain  
‚Ä¢ Code memory ko manipulate karta hai  
‚Ä¢ CPU memory se data uthata hai  

Memory samjhe bina programming magic lagti hai
(aur magic achha nahi hota).


------------------------------------------------------------
13. First Program Announcement
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher announce karta hai:

‚ÄúAaj hum apna FIRST program likhenge.‚Äù

Lekin pehle:
‚Ä¢ Structure samjho  
‚Ä¢ Fear normal hai  


------------------------------------------------------------
14. Program Structure (Flowchart ‚Üí Code)
------------------------------------------------------------

Flowchart:
START ‚Üí PROCESS ‚Üí END  

C++ me:
`main()` = START point  

Execution hamesha `main()` se start hota hai.


------------------------------------------------------------
15. Printing Output ‚Äì cout
------------------------------------------------------------

Screen pe output ke liye:

cout << "Hello Coder Army";

Problem:
Compiler cout ko nahi jaanta.

Solution:
#include <iostream>

iostream provide karta hai:
‚Ä¢ cout  
‚Ä¢ cin  
‚Ä¢ endl  

Header file = feature provider.

------------------------------------------------------------
16. Namespace std ‚Äì Problem & Solution
------------------------------------------------------------

Without namespace:
std::cout << "Hello";   // long ‚ùå

With:
using namespace std;

Now:
cout << "Hello";


------------------------------------------------------------
17. Why Namespace Exists
------------------------------------------------------------

Namespaces prevent:
‚Ä¢ Name conflicts  
‚Ä¢ Library clashes  

std = container of standard names.


------------------------------------------------------------
18. IDE Concept
------------------------------------------------------------

IDE = Integrated Development Environment

Examples:
‚Ä¢ VS Code  
‚Ä¢ CodeBlocks  
‚Ä¢ Online compilers  

IDE helps:
‚Ä¢ Write
‚Ä¢ Compile
‚Ä¢ Run


------------------------------------------------------------
19. Creating First C++ File
------------------------------------------------------------

Steps:
‚Ä¢ Create folder  
‚Ä¢ Create file  
‚Ä¢ Name: first.cpp  

.cpp tells compiler:
‚ÄúThis is a C++ file.‚Äù


------------------------------------------------------------
20. Running First Program
------------------------------------------------------------

If no error:
Program runs successfully.

Errors = learning tool, enemy nahi.


------------------------------------------------------------
21. Insertion Operator (<<)
------------------------------------------------------------

<< = Insertion Operator  
Output stream me data insert karta hai.

Multiple usage allowed.


------------------------------------------------------------
22. New Line Handling
------------------------------------------------------------

Two ways:
1Ô∏è‚É£ endl  
2Ô∏è‚É£ "\n"  

Dono next line pe le jaate hain.


------------------------------------------------------------
23. Printing Text vs Expressions
------------------------------------------------------------

cout << 3 + 2;      // prints 5  
cout << "3 + 2";    // prints 3 + 2  

Quotes = literal  
No quotes = evaluation


------------------------------------------------------------
24. Variables ‚Äì Human Language Analogy
------------------------------------------------------------

Hum use karte hain:
‚Ä¢ Numbers
‚Ä¢ Characters
‚Ä¢ Yes / No  

Computer ko bhi types chahiye.


------------------------------------------------------------
25. Integer Data Type (int)
------------------------------------------------------------

int a = 10;

Meaning:
‚Ä¢ Memory allocate hui  
‚Ä¢ 10 store hua  
‚Ä¢ Usually 4 bytes  


------------------------------------------------------------
26. Why Fixed Size Memory Is Necessary
------------------------------------------------------------

Airplane seat analogy:
‚Ä¢ Seat fixed size ki hoti hai  

Similarly: int = fixed bits

Benefits:
1Ô∏è‚É£ CPU knows kitna read karna hai  
2Ô∏è‚É£ Execution fast hota hai


------------------------------------------------------------
27. Variable Naming Rules
------------------------------------------------------------

Allowed:
‚Ä¢ a  
‚Ä¢ a2  
‚Ä¢ a_b  
‚Ä¢ homeLoan  

Not allowed:
‚Ä¢ Starting with number  


------------------------------------------------------------
28. Declaration v/s Definition
------------------------------------------------------------

Declaration:
int a;

Definition:
a = 10;

Both together:
int a = 10;


------------------------------------------------------------
29. Arithmetic with Variables
------------------------------------------------------------

int a = 10;
int b = 20;
int c = a + b;

Result:
c = 30


------------------------------------------------------------
30. Comments ‚Äì Ignored by Compiler
------------------------------------------------------------

Comments compiler ignore karta hai.

Used for:
‚Ä¢ Explanation
‚Ä¢ Readability


------------------------------------------------------------
31. Character Data Type (char)
------------------------------------------------------------

char c = 'A';

Stored as:
ASCII ‚Üí binary ‚Üí memory

Size:
1 byte


------------------------------------------------------------
32. Boolean Data Type (bool)
------------------------------------------------------------

bool flag = true;

true  ‚Üí 1  
false ‚Üí 0  

Internally numeric.


------------------------------------------------------------
33. Floating Point Types
------------------------------------------------------------

‚Ä¢ float  ‚Üí less precision  
‚Ä¢ double ‚Üí more precision  

Large decimals ‚Üí double preferred.


------------------------------------------------------------
34. Why Not Always Use double?
------------------------------------------------------------

Because:
‚Ä¢ More memory usage  
‚Ä¢ Wasteful for small data  

Rule:
Use smallest sufficient type.


------------------------------------------------------------
35. Negative Numbers ‚Äì Two‚Äôs Complement
------------------------------------------------------------

Problem:
Multiple zero representations ‚ùå

Solution:
Two‚Äôs complement

Benefits:
‚Ä¢ Single zero  
‚Ä¢ Easy arithmetic  
‚Ä¢ Efficient range  


------------------------------------------------------------
36. Memory Efficiency Philosophy
------------------------------------------------------------

Good code:
‚Ä¢ Less memory  
‚Ä¢ Fast execution  
‚Ä¢ Readable  


------------------------------------------------------------
37. Online Compilers
------------------------------------------------------------

Examples:
‚Ä¢ OneCompiler  
‚Ä¢ GeeksforGeeks  
‚Ä¢ LeetCode  

Helpful jab IDE available na ho.


